==Latin==

===Etymology===
{{PIE root|la|dyew}}
Back-formed from the accusative {{m|la|diem}} (at a time when the vowel was still long), from {{der|la|itc-pro|*djēm}}, the accusative of {{m|itc-pro|*djous}}, from {{der|la|ine-pro|*dyḗws||heaven, sky}}. The original nominative survives as {{m|la|*diūs}} in two fossilised phrases: {{m|la|mediusfidius|mē diūs fidius|pos=an interjection}} and {{m|la|nudius|nū diūs tertius|day before yesterday|lit=now (is) the third day}}. The ''d'' in ''diēs'' is a puzzle with some suggesting dialect borrowing and others referring to an etymon ''*diyew-'' via [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievers%27_law#Lindeman Lindeman's Law]. But note the possible Proto-Italic allophony between ''-CjV-'' and ''-CiV-'', which may be the cause for this divergence (''See'' [[WT:AITC]]).

Cognate with {{cog|grc|Ζήν}}, {{cog|xcl|տիւ||daytime}}, {{cog|sga|día}}, {{cog|cy|dydd}}, {{cog|pl|dzień}}. {{cog|en|day}} ([[q.v.]]) is a [[false cognate]]. The Italic stem was also the source of {{m|la|Iovis}}, the genitive of {{m|la|Iuppiter}} and was generally interchangeable with it in earlier times, still shown by the analogical formation {{m|la|Diēspiter}}.

