====Usage notes====
Dates in the Roman calendar were reckoned according to the [[calends]] ({{m|la|kalendae}}), the [[nones]] ({{m|la|nōnae}}), and the [[ides]] ({{m|la|īdūs}}). The calends of every month was its first day; the nones and ides of most months were their 5th and 13th days; and the nones and ides of the four original 31-day months—{{m|la|Mārtius}}, {{m|la|Māius}}, {{m|la|Quīntīlis}} or {{m|la|Iūlius}}, and {{m|la|Octōber}}—were two days later. January 1st was thus {{m|la|kalendae}} {{m|la|Ianuarius|Iānuāriae}} or {{m|la|Ianuarius|Iānuāriī}}. The day preceding any of these three principal days was called its eve ({{m|la|prīdiē}}). January 12th was thus {{m|la|prīdiē}} {{m|la|īdūs}} {{m|la|Ianuarius|Iānuāriās}} or {{m|la|Ianuarius|Iānuāriī}} ({{m|la|pr.}} {{m|la|Id.}} {{m|la|Ian.}}). All other days of the month were expressed by counting inclusively forward to the next of these three principal days and, in early Latin, this was expressed in the ablative. January 11th was thus {{m|la|diē}} {{m|la|tertiō}} {{m|la|ante}} {{m|la|īdūs}} {{m|la|Ianuarius|Iānuāriās}} or {{m|la|Ianuarius|Iānuāriī}} ({{m|la|iii}} {{m|la|Id.}} {{m|la|Ian.}}). By the time of classical Latin, however, the {{m|la|ante}} had moved to the beginning of the expression and it became an accusative absolute: {{m|la|ante}} {{m|la|diem}} {{m|la|tertium}} {{m|la|īdūs}} {{m|la|Ianuarius|Iānuāriās}} or {{m|la|Ianuarius|Iānuāriī}} ({{m|la|a.d.}} {{m|la|iii}} {{m|la|Id.}} {{m|la|Ian}}.).<ref>The British Sundial Society, [http://sundialsoc.org.uk/news/ante-diem-bis-sextum-kalend/ "Ante Diem Bis Sextum Kalendras Martii"], 2016.</ref> In this form, the date functioned as a single indeclinable noun and could serve as the object of prepositions such as {{m|la|ex}} and {{m|la|in}}.<ref>Beck, Charles, [https://books.google.com/books?id=clMQAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover ''Latin Syntax, Chiefly from the German of C. G. Zumpt''] (1838), Boston: Charles C. Little & James Brown, [https://books.google.com/books?id=uJgQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA176 p. 176].</ref>

Unlike most fifth-declension nouns, ''diēs'' is not exclusively feminine. It was typically masculine, particularly in the plural. It appears as a feminine noun when being personified as a goddess, in some specific dates, in reference to the passing of time, and occasionally in other contexts.

